What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data consists of 183412 rows each representing a rental record. For each rental, the start and end station coordinates and id are recorded as well as the ride start time, end time and duration of the ride. The bike id is also recorded as well as some basic customer demographics such as birth year, gender and whether they are subscribed or not. Some variables are numerical such as times and coordinates, some are categorical such as gender(Male, Female, Other) and user type(Subscriber, Customer).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

features of interest are whether there is a relatiosnship between customer type or gender and rental patterns.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

user_type, member_gender and counts.

In this section, I will be looking at how different variables are distributed.

The vast majority of trips take less than 30 minutes and more specifically most are in the range below 15 minutes.

We can also see that rentals peak around 8-9 am and again around 5 pm. From these two observations we can see that most people use the rented bike for commute to or from work.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

There was a distinct pattern in rentals manifesting in a large drop in rentals over the weekend as well as peaks in the morning and the afternoon. An intersting distribution was that of ride durations as most rides are short only lasting less than 15 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Some gender data was missing so in related plots, the rows containing missing values were dropped. To display the time in an informative way, the data had to be converted to datetime format and different plots used different parts of the information such as the hour or the day of the week.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Customers had a different rental pattern than that of subscribers across week days but similar patterns within the day. They also had same ride duration ranges as subscribers. Gender, on the other hand had no influence on rental rates in different times.

Another point of interest is that the daily pattern of rentals for different hours persists across all week days

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There are more older male users than non-males of smiliar age groups.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Weekly usage patterns are persistent in all areas. Surprisingly, there is no difference in start and end times between Monday and Sunday was also somewhat surprising since it was expected that peoplr's behaviour patterns can change during weekends.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Some areas have more longer trips than others. Interestingly, the places with more long rides also have a higher ratio of Customers to Subscribers which might be due to these places having more attractions.
